140 /**
141  Calls contextualize() on every node in the array.
142 */
143 template <class Node_type, class Parse_context_type>
144 bool contextualize_nodes(Mem_root_array_YY<Node_type *> nodes,
145  Parse_context_type *pc) {
146  for (Node_type *i : nodes)
147  if (i->contextualize(pc)) return true;
148  return false;
149 }
150 
151 /**
152  Base class for all top-level nodes of SQL statements
153 
154  @ingroup ptn_stmt
155 */
156 class Parse_tree_root {

162  Parse_tree_root() {}
163 
164  public:
165  virtual Sql_cmd *make_cmd(THD *thd) = 0;
166 };

199 class PT_order_expr : public Parse_tree_node, public ORDER {
200  typedef Parse_tree_node super;
201 
202  public:
203  PT_order_expr(Item *item_arg, enum_order dir) {
204  item_ptr = item_arg;
205  direction = (dir == ORDER_DESC) ? ORDER_DESC : ORDER_ASC;
206  }
207 
208  bool contextualize(Parse_context *pc) override;
209 };
210 
211 class PT_order_list : public Parse_tree_node {
212  typedef Parse_tree_node super;
213 
214  public:
215  SQL_I_List<ORDER> value;
216 
217  public:
218  bool contextualize(Parse_context *pc) override {
219  if (super::contextualize(pc)) return true;
220  for (ORDER *o = value.first; o != nullptr; o = o->next) {
221  if (static_cast<PT_order_expr *>(o)->contextualize(pc)) return true;
222  }
223  return false;
224  }
225 
226  void push_back(PT_order_expr *order) {
227  order->item = &order->item_ptr;
228  order->used_alias = false;
229  order->used = 0;
230  order->is_position = false;
231  value.link_in_list(order, &order->next);
232  }
233 };
234 
235 class PT_gorder_list : public PT_order_list {

237 
238  public:
239  bool contextualize(Parse_context *pc) override {
240  return super::contextualize(pc);
241  }
242 };

244 /**
245  Represents an element of the WITH list:
246  WITH [...], [...] SELECT ...,
247  ^ or ^
248  i.e. a Common Table Expression (CTE, or Query Name in SQL99 terms).
249 */
250 class PT_common_table_expr : public Parse_tree_node {
251  typedef Parse_tree_node super;
252 
253  public:
254  explicit PT_common_table_expr(const LEX_STRING &name,
255  const LEX_STRING &subq_text,
256  uint subq_text_offset, PT_subquery *sn,
257  const Create_col_name_list *column_names,
258  MEM_ROOT *mem_root);
259 
260  /// The name after AS
261  const LEX_STRING &name() const { return m_name; }
262  /**
263  @param thd Thread handler
264  @param[out] node PT_subquery
265  @returns a PT_subquery to attach to a table reference for this CTE
266  */
267  bool make_subquery_node(THD *thd, PT_subquery **node);
268  /**
269  @param tl Table reference to match
270  @param in_self If this is a recursive reference
271  @param[out] found Is set to true/false if matches or not
272  @returns true if error
273  */
274  bool match_table_ref(TABLE_LIST *tl, bool in_self, bool *found);
275  /**
276  @returns true if 'other' is the same instance as 'this'
277  */
278  bool is(const Common_table_expr *other) const {
279  return other == &m_postparse;
280  }
281  void print(const THD *thd, String *str, enum_query_type query_type);
282 
283  private:
284  LEX_STRING m_name;
285  /// Raw text of query expression (including parentheses)
286  const LEX_STRING m_subq_text;
287  /**
288  Offset in bytes of m_subq_text in original statement which had the WITH
289  clause.
290  */
291  uint m_subq_text_offset;
292  /// Parsed version of subq_text
293  PT_subquery *const m_subq_node;
294  /// List of explicitely specified column names; if empty, no list.
295  const Create_col_name_list m_column_names;
296  /**
297  A TABLE_LIST representing a CTE needs access to the WITH list
298  element it derives from. However, in order to:
299  - limit the members which TABLE_LIST can access
300  - avoid including this header file everywhere TABLE_LIST needs to access
301  these members,
302  these members are relocated into a separate inferior object whose
303  declaration is in table.h, like that of TABLE_LIST. It's the "postparse"
304  part. TABLE_LIST accesses this inferior object only.
305  */
306  Common_table_expr m_postparse;
307 
308  friend bool SELECT_LEX_UNIT::clear_correlated_query_blocks();
309 };
310 
311 /**
312  Represents the WITH list.
313  WITH [...], [...] SELECT ...,
314  ^^^^^^^^^^^^
315 */
316 class PT_with_list : public Parse_tree_node {
317  typedef Parse_tree_node super;
318 
319  public:
320  /// @param mem_root where interior objects are allocated
321  explicit PT_with_list(MEM_ROOT *mem_root) : m_elements(mem_root) {}
322  bool push_back(PT_common_table_expr *el);
323  const Mem_root_array<PT_common_table_expr *> &elements() const {
324  return m_elements;
325  }
326 
327  private:
328  Mem_root_array<PT_common_table_expr *> m_elements;
329 };

331 /**
332  Represents the WITH clause:
333  WITH [...], [...] SELECT ...,
334  ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
335 */
336 class PT_with_clause : public Parse_tree_node {
337  typedef Parse_tree_node super;
338 
339  public:
340  PT_with_clause(const PT_with_list *l, bool r)
341  : m_list(l), m_recursive(r), m_most_inner_in_parsing(nullptr) {}
342 
343  bool contextualize(Parse_context *pc) override;
344 
345  /**
346  Looks up a table reference into the list of CTEs.
347  @param tl Table reference to look up
348  @param[out] found Is set to true/false if found or not
349  @returns true if error
350  */
351  bool lookup(TABLE_LIST *tl, PT_common_table_expr **found);
352  /**
353  Call this to record in the WITH clause that we are contextualizing the
354  CTE definition inserted in table reference 'tl'.
355  @returns information which the caller must provide to
356  leave_parsing_definition().
357  */
358  const TABLE_LIST *enter_parsing_definition(TABLE_LIST *tl) {
359  auto old = m_most_inner_in_parsing;
360  m_most_inner_in_parsing = tl;
361  return old;
362  }
363  void leave_parsing_definition(const TABLE_LIST *old) {
364  m_most_inner_in_parsing = old;
365  }
366  void print(const THD *thd, String *str, enum_query_type query_type);
367 
368  private:
369  /// All CTEs of this clause
370  const PT_with_list *const m_list;
371  /// True if the user has specified the RECURSIVE keyword.
372  const bool m_recursive;
373  /**
374  The innermost CTE reference which we're parsing at the
375  moment. Used to detect forward references, loops and recursiveness.
376  */
377  const TABLE_LIST *m_most_inner_in_parsing;
378 
379  friend bool SELECT_LEX_UNIT::clear_correlated_query_blocks();
380 };

404 class PT_table_reference : public Parse_tree_node {
405  public:
406  TABLE_LIST *value;
407 
408  /**
409  Lets us build a parse tree top-down, which is necessary due to the
410  context-dependent nature of the join syntax. This function adds
411  the @<table_ref@> cross join as the left-most leaf in this join tree
412  rooted at this node.
413 
414  @todo: comment on non-join PT_table_reference objects
415 
416  @param cj This @<table ref@> will be added if it represents a cross join.
417 
418  @return The new top-level join.
419  */
420  virtual PT_joined_table *add_cross_join(PT_cross_join *cj);
421 };

514 class PT_joined_table : public PT_table_reference {
515  typedef PT_table_reference super;
516 
517  protected:
518  PT_table_reference *tab1_node;
519  POS join_pos;
520  PT_joined_table_type m_type;
521  PT_table_reference *tab2_node;
522 
523  TABLE_LIST *tr1;
524  TABLE_LIST *tr2;
525 
526  public:
527  PT_joined_table(PT_table_reference *tab1_node_arg, const POS &join_pos_arg,
528  PT_joined_table_type type, PT_table_reference *tab2_node_arg)
529  : tab1_node(tab1_node_arg),
530  join_pos(join_pos_arg),
531  m_type(type),
532  tab2_node(tab2_node_arg),
533  tr1(nullptr),
534  tr2(nullptr) {
535  static_assert(is_single_bit(JTT_INNER), "not a single bit");
536  static_assert(is_single_bit(JTT_STRAIGHT), "not a single bit");
537  static_assert(is_single_bit(JTT_NATURAL), "not a single bit");
538  static_assert(is_single_bit(JTT_LEFT), "not a single bit");
539  static_assert(is_single_bit(JTT_RIGHT), "not a single bit");
540 
541  DBUG_ASSERT(type == JTT_INNER || type == JTT_STRAIGHT_INNER ||
542  type == JTT_NATURAL_INNER || type == JTT_NATURAL_LEFT ||
543  type == JTT_NATURAL_RIGHT || type == JTT_LEFT ||
544  type == JTT_RIGHT);
545  }
546 
547  /**
548  Adds the cross join to this join operation. The cross join is nested as
549  the table reference on the left-hand side.
550  */
551  PT_joined_table *add_cross_join(PT_cross_join *cj) override {
552  tab1_node = tab1_node->add_cross_join(cj);
553  return this;
554  }
555 
556  /// Adds the table reference as the right-hand side of this join.
557  void add_rhs(PT_table_reference *table) {
558  DBUG_ASSERT(tab2_node == nullptr);
559  tab2_node = table;
560  }
561 
562  bool contextualize(Parse_context *pc) override;
563 
564  /// This class is being inherited, it should thus be abstract.
565  ~PT_joined_table() override = 0;
566 
567  protected:
568  bool contextualize_tabs(Parse_context *pc);
569 };
570 
571 inline PT_joined_table::~PT_joined_table() {}

645 class PT_locking_clause : public Parse_tree_node {
646  public:
647  PT_locking_clause(Lock_strength strength, Locked_row_action action)
648  : m_lock_strength(strength), m_locked_row_action(action) {}
649 
650  bool contextualize(Parse_context *pc) final;
651 
652  virtual bool set_lock_for_tables(Parse_context *pc) = 0;
653 
654  Locked_row_action action() const { return m_locked_row_action; }
655 
656  protected:
657  Lock_descriptor get_lock_descriptor() const {
658  thr_lock_type lock_type = TL_IGNORE;
659  switch (m_lock_strength) {
660  case Lock_strength::UPDATE:
661  lock_type = TL_WRITE;
662  break;
663  case Lock_strength::SHARE:
664  lock_type = TL_READ_WITH_SHARED_LOCKS;
665  break;
666  }
667 
668  return {lock_type, static_cast<thr_locked_row_action>(action())};
669  }
670 
671  private:
672  Lock_strength m_lock_strength;
673  Locked_row_action m_locked_row_action;
674 };
675 
676 class PT_query_block_locking_clause : public PT_locking_clause {
677  public:
678  explicit PT_query_block_locking_clause(
679  Lock_strength strength,
680  Locked_row_action action = Locked_row_action::WAIT)
681  : PT_locking_clause(strength, action) {}
682 
683  bool set_lock_for_tables(Parse_context *pc) override;

708 class PT_locking_clause_list : public Parse_tree_node {
709  public:
710  PT_locking_clause_list(MEM_ROOT *mem_root) {
711  m_locking_clauses.init(mem_root);
712  }
713 
714  bool push_back(PT_locking_clause *locking_clause) {
715  return m_locking_clauses.push_back(locking_clause);
716  }
717 
718  bool contextualize(Parse_context *pc) override {
719  for (auto locking_clause : m_locking_clauses)
720  if (locking_clause->contextualize(pc)) return true;
721  return false;
722  }

724  private:

727 
728 class PT_query_expression_body : public Parse_tree_node {
729  public:
730  virtual bool is_union() const = 0;
731 
732  /**
733  True if this query expression can absorb an extraneous order by/limit
734  clause. The `ORDER BY`/`LIMIT` syntax is mostly consistestent, i.e. a
735  trailing clause may not refer to the tables in the `<query primary>`, with
736  one glaring exception:
737 
738  (...( SELECT ... )...) ORDER BY ...
739 
740  If the nested query expression doesn't contain `ORDER BY`, the statement
741  is interpreted as if the `ORDER BY` was absorbed by the innermost query
742  expression, i.e.:
743 
744  (...( SELECT ... ORDER BY ... )...)
745 
746  There is no rewriting of the parse tree nor AST happening here, the
747  transformation is done by the contextualizer (see
748  PT_query_expression::contextualize_order_and_limit), which interprets the
749  parse tree, and builds the AST according to this interpretation. This
750  interpretation is governed by the following rule: An `ORDER BY` can be
751  absorbed if none the nested query expressions contains an `ORDER BY` *or*
752  `LIMIT`. The rule is complex, so here are some examples for illustration:
753 
754  In these cases the `ORDER BY` *is* absorbed:
755 
756  ( SELECT * FROM t1 ) ORDER BY t1.a;
757  (( SELECT * FROM t1 )) ORDER BY t1.a;
758 
759  In these cases the ORDER BY is *not* absorbed:
760 
761  ( SELECT * FROM t1 ORDER BY 1 ) ORDER BY t1.a;
762  (( SELECT * FROM t1 ) ORDER BY 1 ) ORDER BY t1.a;
763  ( SELECT * FROM t1 LIMIT 1 ) ORDER BY t1.a;
764  (( SELECT * FROM t1 ) LIMIT 1 ) ORDER BY t1.a;
765 
766  The same happens with `LIMIT`, obviously, but the optimizer is freeer to
767  choose when to apply the limit, and there are name no resolution issues
768  involved.
769 
770  @param order True if the outer query block has the ORDER BY clause.
771  @param limit True if the outer query block has the LIMIT clause.
772  */
773  virtual bool can_absorb_order_and_limit(bool order, bool limit) const = 0;
774  virtual bool has_into_clause() const = 0;
775  virtual bool has_trailing_into_clause() const = 0;
776 
777  virtual bool is_table_value_constructor() const = 0;
778  virtual PT_insert_values_list *get_row_value_list() const = 0;
779 };
780

1274 /**
1275  Parse tree node for a single of a window extent's borders,
1276  cf. <window frame extent> in SQL 2003.
1277 */
1278 class PT_border : public Parse_tree_node {
1279  friend class Window;
1280  Item *m_value{nullptr}; ///< only relevant iff m_border_type == WBT_VALUE_*
1281  public:
1282  enum_window_border_type m_border_type;
1283  const bool m_date_time;
1284  interval_type m_int_type;
1285 
1286  ///< For unbounded border
1287  PT_border(enum_window_border_type type)
1288  : m_border_type(type), m_date_time(false) {
1289  DBUG_ASSERT(type != WBT_VALUE_PRECEDING && type != WBT_VALUE_FOLLOWING);
1290  }
1291 
1292  ///< For bounded non-temporal border, e.g. 2 PRECEDING: 'value' is 2.
1293  PT_border(enum_window_border_type type, Item *value)
1294  : m_value(value), m_border_type(type), m_date_time(false) {}
1295 
1296  ///< For bounded INTERVAL 2 DAYS, 'value' is 2, int_type is DAYS.
1297  PT_border(enum_window_border_type type, Item *value, interval_type int_type)
1298  : m_value(value),
1299  m_border_type(type),
1300  m_date_time(true),
1301  m_int_type(int_type) {}
1302 
1303  ///< @returns the '2' in '2 PRECEDING' or 'INTERVAL 2 DAYS PRECEDING'
1304  Item *border() const { return m_value; }
1305  /// Need such low-level access so that fix_fields updates the right pointer
1306  Item **border_ptr() { return &m_value; }
1307 
1308  /**
1309  @returns Addition operator for computation of frames, nullptr if error.
1310  @param order_expr Expression to add/substract to
1311  @param prec true if PRECEDING
1312  @param asc true if ASC
1313  @param window only used for error generation
1314  */
1315  Item *build_addop(Item_cache *order_expr, bool prec, bool asc,
1316  const Window *window);
1317 };
1318 
1319 /**
1320  Parse tree node for one or both of a window extent's borders, cf.
1321  <window frame extent> in SQL 2003.
1322 */
1323 class PT_borders : public Parse_tree_node {
1324  PT_border *m_borders[2];
1325  friend class PT_frame;
1326 
1327  public:
1328  /**
1329  Constructor.
1330 
1331  Frames of the form "frame_start no_frame_end" are translated during
1332  parsing to "BETWEEN frame_start AND CURRENT ROW". So both 'start' and
1333  'end' are non-nullptr.
1334  */
1335  PT_borders(PT_border *start, PT_border *end) {
1336  m_borders[0] = start;
1337  m_borders[1] = end;
1338  }
1339 };
1340

1347 
1348  public:

1350  // enum_window_frame_exclusion exclusion() { return m_exclusion; }

1353 /**
1354  Parse tree node for a window's frame, cf. the <window frame clause>
1355  in SQL 2003.

1357 class PT_frame : public Parse_tree_node {

1365 
1366  /// If true, this is an artificial frame, not specified by the user
1367  bool m_originally_absent = false;
1368 
1369  PT_frame(enum_window_frame_unit unit, PT_borders *from_to,
1370  PT_exclusion *exclusion)
1371  : m_unit(unit),

1379 class PT_query_specification : public PT_query_primary {
1380  typedef PT_query_primary super;
1381

1383  Query_options options;
1384  PT_item_list *item_list;
1385  PT_into_destination *opt_into1;
1386  const bool m_is_from_clause_implicit;
1387  Mem_root_array_YY<PT_table_reference *> from_clause; // empty list for DUAL
1388  Item *opt_where_clause;
1389  PT_group *opt_group_clause;
1390  Item *opt_having_clause;
1391  PT_window_list *opt_window_clause;
1392 
1393  public:
1394  PT_query_specification(
1395  PT_hint_list *opt_hints_arg, const Query_options &options_arg,
1396  PT_item_list *item_list_arg, PT_into_destination *opt_into1_arg,
1397  const Mem_root_array_YY<PT_table_reference *> &from_clause_arg,
1398  Item *opt_where_clause_arg, PT_group *opt_group_clause_arg,
1399  Item *opt_having_clause_arg, PT_window_list *opt_window_clause_arg,
1400  bool implicit_from_clause)
1401  : opt_hints(opt_hints_arg),
1402  options(options_arg),
1403  item_list(item_list_arg),
1404  opt_into1(opt_into1_arg),
1405  m_is_from_clause_implicit{implicit_from_clause},
1406  from_clause(from_clause_arg),
1407  opt_where_clause(opt_where_clause_arg),
1408  opt_group_clause(opt_group_clause_arg),
1409  opt_having_clause(opt_having_clause_arg),
1410  opt_window_clause(opt_window_clause_arg) {
1411  DBUG_ASSERT(implicit_from_clause ? from_clause.empty() : true);
1412  }
1413 
1414  PT_query_specification(
1415  const Query_options &options_arg, PT_item_list *item_list_arg,
1416  const Mem_root_array_YY<PT_table_reference *> &from_clause_arg,
1417  Item *opt_where_clause_arg)
1418  : opt_hints(nullptr),
1419  options(options_arg),
1420  item_list(item_list_arg),
1421  opt_into1(nullptr),
1422  m_is_from_clause_implicit{true},
1423  from_clause(from_clause_arg),
1424  opt_where_clause(opt_where_clause_arg),
1425  opt_group_clause(nullptr),
1426  opt_having_clause(nullptr),
1427  opt_window_clause(nullptr) {}
1428 
1429  PT_query_specification(const Query_options &options_arg,
1430  PT_item_list *item_list_arg)
1431  : opt_hints(nullptr),
1432  options(options_arg),
1433  item_list(item_list_arg),
1434  opt_into1(nullptr),
1435  m_is_from_clause_implicit{false},
1436  from_clause{},
1437  opt_where_clause(nullptr),
1438  opt_group_clause(nullptr),
1439  opt_having_clause(nullptr),
1440  opt_window_clause(nullptr) {}
1441 
1442  bool contextualize(Parse_context *pc) override;
1443 
1444  bool has_into_clause() const override { return opt_into1 != nullptr; }
1445  bool has_trailing_into_clause() const override {
1446  return (has_into_clause() && is_implicit_from_clause() &&
1447  opt_where_clause == nullptr && opt_group_clause == nullptr &&
1448  opt_having_clause == nullptr && opt_window_clause == nullptr);
1449  }
1450 
1451  bool is_union() const override { return false; }
1452 
1453  bool can_absorb_order_and_limit(bool, bool) const override { return true; }
1454 
1455  bool is_table_value_constructor() const override { return false; }
1456  PT_insert_values_list *get_row_value_list() const override { return nullptr; }
1457 
1458  private:
1459  bool is_implicit_from_clause() const { return m_is_from_clause_implicit; }
1460 };

1497 class PT_query_expression final : public PT_query_primary {
1498  public:
1499  PT_query_expression(PT_with_clause *with_clause,
1500  PT_query_expression_body *body, PT_order *order,
1501  PT_limit_clause *limit)
1502  : m_body(body),
1503  m_order(order),
1504  m_limit(limit),
1505  m_with_clause(with_clause) {}
1506 
1507  PT_query_expression(PT_query_expression_body *body, PT_order *order,
1508  PT_limit_clause *limit)
1509  : PT_query_expression(nullptr, body, order, limit) {}
1510 
1511  explicit PT_query_expression(PT_query_expression_body *body)
1512  : PT_query_expression(body, nullptr, nullptr) {}
1513 
1514  bool contextualize(Parse_context *pc) override;
1515 
1516  bool is_union() const override { return m_body->is_union(); }
1517 
1518  bool has_into_clause() const override { return m_body->has_into_clause(); }
1519  bool has_trailing_into_clause() const override {
1520  return (m_body->has_trailing_into_clause() && m_order == nullptr &&
1521  m_limit == nullptr);
1522  }
1523 
1524  bool can_absorb_order_and_limit(bool order, bool limit) const override {
1525  if (m_body->is_union()) {
1526  return false;
1527  }
1528  if (m_order == nullptr && m_limit == nullptr) {
1529  /*
1530  It is safe to push ORDER and/or LIMIT down in:
1531 
1532  (SELECT ...<no order or limit clauses>) ORDER BY ... LIMIT ...;
1533  (SELECT ...<no order or limit clauses>) ORDER BY ...;
1534  (SELECT ...<no order or limit clauses>) LIMIT ...;
1535  */
1536  return true;
1537  }
1538  if (m_limit != nullptr && !order && limit) {
1539  /*
1540  In MySQL, it is ok(*) to push LIMIT down in:
1541 
1542  (SELECT ... [ORDER BY ...] LIMIT a) LIMIT b;
1543 
1544  *) MySQL doesn't follow the standard when overwriting `LIMIT a` with
1545  `LIMIT b` if a < b. Moreover, the result of:
1546 
1547  (SELECT ... ORDER BY order1 LIMIT a) ORDER BY order1 LIMIT b; (1)
1548 
1549  can diverge from:
1550 
1551  (SELECT ... ORDER BY order1 LIMIT a) LIMIT b; (2)
1552 
1553  since the example (1) never overwrites `LIMIT a` with `LIMIT b`,
1554  while the example (2) does overwrite.
1555 
1556  TODO: add a warning, deprecate and replace this behavior with the
1557  standard one.
1558  */
1559  return true;
1560  }
1561  return false;
1562  }
1563 
1564  bool is_table_value_constructor() const override {
1565  return m_body->is_table_value_constructor();
1566  }
1567 
1568  PT_insert_values_list *get_row_value_list() const override {
1569  return m_body->get_row_value_list();
1570  }
1571 
1572  private:
1573  /**
1574  Contextualizes the order and limit clauses, re-interpreting them according
1575  to the rules. If the `<query expression body>` can absorb the clauses,
1576  they are simply contextualized into the current SELECT_LEX. If not, we
1577  have to create the "fake" SELECT_LEX unless there is one already
1578  (SELECT_LEX_UNIT::new_union_query() is known to do this.)
1579 
1580  @see PT_query_expression::can_absorb_order_and_limit()
1581  */
1582  bool contextualize_order_and_limit(Parse_context *pc);
1583 
1584  PT_query_expression_body *m_body;
1585  PT_order *m_order;
1586  PT_limit_clause *m_limit;
1587  PT_with_clause *m_with_clause;
1588 };
1589 
1590 /*
1591  After the removal of the `... <locking_clause> <into_clause>` syntax
1592  PT_locking will disappear.
1593 */
1594 class PT_locking final : public PT_query_primary {
1595  using super = PT_query_primary;
1596 
1597  public:
1598  PT_locking(PT_query_expression_body *qe,
1599  PT_locking_clause_list *locking_clauses)
1600  : m_query_expression{qe}, m_locking_clauses{locking_clauses} {}
1601 
1602  bool contextualize(Parse_context *pc) override {
1603  return (super::contextualize(pc) || m_query_expression->contextualize(pc) ||
1604  m_locking_clauses->contextualize(pc));
1605  }
1606 
1607  bool is_union() const override { return m_query_expression->is_union(); }
1608 
1609  bool has_into_clause() const override {
1610  return m_query_expression->has_into_clause();
1611  }
1612  bool has_trailing_into_clause() const override { return false; }
1613 
1614  bool can_absorb_order_and_limit(bool order, bool limit) const override {
1615  return m_query_expression->can_absorb_order_and_limit(order, limit);
1616  }
1617 
1618  bool is_table_value_constructor() const override {
1619  return m_query_expression->is_table_value_constructor();
1620  }
1621 
1622  PT_insert_values_list *get_row_value_list() const override {
1623  return m_query_expression->get_row_value_list();
1624  }
1625 
1626  private:
1627  PT_query_expression_body *const m_query_expression;
1628  PT_locking_clause_list *const m_locking_clauses;
1629 };

1884  const LEX_CSTRING &opt_values_table_alias_arg,
1885  Create_col_name_list *opt_values_column_list_arg,
1886  PT_item_list *opt_on_duplicate_column_list_arg,
1887  PT_item_list *opt_on_duplicate_value_list_arg)
1888  : is_replace(is_replace_arg),
1889  opt_hints(opt_hints_arg),
1890  lock_option(lock_option_arg),
1891  ignore(ignore_arg),
1892  table_ident(table_ident_arg),
1893  opt_use_partition(opt_use_partition_arg),
1894  column_list(column_list_arg),
1895  row_value_list(row_value_list_arg),
1896  insert_query_expression(insert_query_expression_arg),
1897  opt_values_table_alias(opt_values_table_alias_arg.str),
1898  opt_values_column_list(opt_values_column_list_arg),
1899  opt_on_duplicate_column_list(opt_on_duplicate_column_list_arg),
1900  opt_on_duplicate_value_list(opt_on_duplicate_value_list_arg) {
1901  // REPLACE statement can't have IGNORE flag:
1902  DBUG_ASSERT(!is_replace || !ignore);
1903  // REPLACE statement can't have ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE clause:
1904  DBUG_ASSERT(!is_replace || opt_on_duplicate_column_list == nullptr);
1905  // INSERT/REPLACE ... SELECT can't have VALUES clause:
1906  DBUG_ASSERT((row_value_list != nullptr) ^
1907  (insert_query_expression != nullptr));
1908  // ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE: column and value arrays must have same sizes:
1909  DBUG_ASSERT((opt_on_duplicate_column_list == nullptr &&
1910  opt_on_duplicate_value_list == nullptr) ||
1911  (opt_on_duplicate_column_list->elements() ==
1912  opt_on_duplicate_value_list->elements()));
1913  }
1914 
1915  Sql_cmd *make_cmd(THD *thd) override;
1916 
1917  private:
1918  bool has_select() const { return insert_query_expression != nullptr; }
1919 };
1920

1922  sp_name *proc_name;
1923  PT_item_list *opt_expr_list;
1924 
1925  public:

1927  : proc_name(proc_name_arg), opt_expr_list(opt_expr_list_arg) {}

1929  Sql_cmd *make_cmd(THD *thd) override;

1944 /**
1945  Top-level node for the CREATE [OR REPLACE] SPATIAL REFERENCE SYSTEM statement.
1946 
1947  @ingroup ptn_stmt
1948 */
1949 class PT_create_srs final : public Parse_tree_root {
1950  /// The SQL command object.
1951  Sql_cmd_create_srs sql_cmd;
1952  /// Whether OR REPLACE is specified.
1953  bool m_or_replace;
1954  /// Whether IF NOT EXISTS is specified.
1955  bool m_if_not_exists;
1956  /// SRID of the SRS to create.
1957  ///
1958  /// The range is larger than that of gis::srid_t, so it must be
1959  /// verified to be less than the uint32 maximum value.
1960  unsigned long long m_srid;
1961  /// All attributes except SRID.
1962  const Sql_cmd_srs_attributes m_attributes;
1963 
1964  /// Check if a UTF-8 string contains control characters.
1965  ///
1966  /// @note This function only checks single byte control characters (U+0000 to
1967  /// U+001F, and U+007F). There are some control characters at U+0080 to U+00A0
1968  /// that are not detected by this function.
1969  ///
1970  /// @param str The string.
1971  /// @param length Length of the string.
1972  ///
1973  /// @retval false The string contains no control characters.
1974  /// @retval true The string contains at least one control character.
1975  bool contains_control_char(char *str, size_t length) {
1976  for (size_t pos = 0; pos < length; pos++) {
1977  if (std::iscntrl(str[pos])) return true;
1978  }
1979  return false;
1980  }
1981 
1982  public:
1983  PT_create_srs(unsigned long long srid,
1984  const Sql_cmd_srs_attributes &attributes, bool or_replace,
1985  bool if_not_exists)
1986  : m_or_replace(or_replace),
1987  m_if_not_exists(if_not_exists),
1988  m_srid(srid),
1989  m_attributes(attributes) {}
1990 
1991  Sql_cmd *make_cmd(THD *thd) override;
1992 };
1993

2003  ///
2004  /// The range is larger than that of gis::srid_t, so it must be
2005  /// verified to be less than the uint32 maximum value.
2006  unsigned long long m_srid;
2007 
2008  public:

2010  : sql_cmd(srid, if_exists), m_srid(srid) {}
2011

2032 /**

2034  sql_lex.h
2035 */
2036 class PT_base_index_option : public Table_ddl_node {};
2037 
2038 /**
2039  A key part specification.
2040 
2041  This can either be a "normal" key part (a key part that points to a column),
2042  or this can be a functional key part (a key part that points to an
2043  expression).
2044 */
2045 class PT_key_part_specification : public Parse_tree_node {
2046  typedef Parse_tree_node super;
2047 
2048  public:
2049  /**
2050  Constructor for a functional key part.
2051 
2052  @param expression The expression to index.
2053  @param order The direction of the index.
2054  */
2055  PT_key_part_specification(Item *expression, enum_order order);
2056 
2057  /**
2058  Constructor for a "normal" key part. That is a key part that points to a
2059  column and not an expression.
2060 
2061  @param column_name The column name that this key part points to.
2062  @param order The direction of the index.
2063  @param prefix_length How many bytes or characters this key part should
2064  index, or zero if it should index the entire column.
2065  */
2066  PT_key_part_specification(const LEX_CSTRING &column_name, enum_order order,
2067  int prefix_length);
2068 
2069  /**
2070  Contextualize this key part specification. This will also call itemize on
2071  the indexed expression if this is a functional key part.
2072 
2073  @param pc The parse context
2074 
2075  @retval true on error
2076  @retval false on success
2077  */
2078  bool contextualize(Parse_context *pc) override;
2079 
2080  /**
2081  Get the indexed expression. The caller must ensure that has_expression()
2082  returns true before calling this.
2083 
2084  @returns The indexed expression
2085  */
2086  Item *get_expression() const {
2087  DBUG_ASSERT(has_expression());
2088  return m_expression;
2089  }
2090 
2091  /**
2092  @returns The direction of the index: ORDER_ASC, ORDER_DESC or
2093  ORDER_NOT_RELEVANT in case the user didn't explicitly specify a
2094  direction.
2095  */
2096  enum_order get_order() const { return m_order; }
2097 
2098  /**
2099  @retval true if the user explicitly specified a direction (asc/desc).
2100  @retval false if the user didn't explicitly specify a direction.
2101  */
2102  bool is_explicit() const { return get_order() != ORDER_NOT_RELEVANT; }
2103 
2104  /**
2105  @retval true if the key part contains an expression (and thus is a
2106  functional key part).
2107  @retval false if the key part doesn't contain an expression.
2108  */
2109  bool has_expression() const { return m_expression != nullptr; }
2110 
2111  /**
2112  Get the column that this key part points to. This is only valid if this
2113  key part isn't a functional index. The caller must thus check the return
2114  value of has_expression() before calling this function.
2115 
2116  @returns The column that this key part points to.
2117  */
2118  LEX_CSTRING get_column_name() const {
2119  DBUG_ASSERT(!has_expression());
2120  return m_column_name;
2121  }
2122 
2123  /**
2124  @returns The number of bytes that this key part should index. If the column
2125  this key part points to is a non-binary column, this is the number
2126  of characters. Returns zero if the entire column should be indexed.
2127  */
2128  int get_prefix_length() const { return m_prefix_length; }
2129 
2130  private:
2131  /**
2132  The indexed expression in case this is a functional key part. Only valid if
2133  has_expression() returns true.
2134  */
2135  Item *m_expression;
2136 
2137  /// The direction of the index.
2138  enum_order m_order;
2139 
2140  /// The name of the column that this key part indexes.
2141  LEX_CSTRING m_column_name;
2142 
2143  /**
2144  If this is greater than zero, it represents how many bytes of the column
2145  that is indexed. Note that for non-binary columns (VARCHAR, TEXT etc), this
2146  is the number of characters.
2147  */
2148  int m_prefix_length;
2149 };

2488 
2489  public:
2490  explicit PT_ternary_create_table_option(Ternary_option value)
2491  : value(value) {}
2492 
2493  bool contextualize(Table_ddl_parse_context *pc) override {
2494  if (super::contextualize(pc)) return true;
2495  pc->create_info->table_options &= ~(Yes | No);
2496  switch (value) {
2497  case Ternary_option::ON:
2498  pc->create_info->table_options |= Yes;
2499  break;
2500  case Ternary_option::OFF:
2501  pc->create_info->table_options |= No;
2502  break;
2503  case Ternary_option::DEFAULT:
2504  break;
2505  default:
2506  DBUG_ASSERT(false);
2507  }
2508  pc->create_info->used_fields |= Property_flag;
2509  return false;
2510  }
2511 };
2512 
2513 /**
2514  Node for the @SQL{PACK_KEYS [=] @B{1|0|DEFAULT}} table option
2515 
2516  @ingroup ptn_create_or_alter_table_options
2517 
2518  PACK_KEYS | Constructor parameter
2519  ----------|----------------------
2520  1 | Ternary_option::ON
2521  0 | Ternary_option::OFF
2522  DEFAULT | Ternary_option::DEFAULT
2523 */
2524 typedef PT_ternary_create_table_option<HA_CREATE_USED_PACK_KEYS, // flag
2525  0, // DEFAULT
2526  HA_OPTION_PACK_KEYS, // ON
2527  HA_OPTION_NO_PACK_KEYS> // OFF
2528  PT_create_pack_keys_option;
2529 
2530 /**
2531  Node for the @SQL{STATS_PERSISTENT [=] @B{1|0|DEFAULT}} table option
2532 
2533  @ingroup ptn_create_or_alter_table_options
2534 
2535  STATS_PERSISTENT | Constructor parameter
2536  -----------------|----------------------
2537  1 | Ternary_option::ON
2538  0 | Ternary_option::OFF
2539  DEFAULT | Ternary_option::DEFAULT
2540 */
2541 typedef PT_ternary_create_table_option<HA_CREATE_USED_STATS_PERSISTENT, // flag
2542  0, // DEFAULT
2543  HA_OPTION_STATS_PERSISTENT, // ON
2544  HA_OPTION_NO_STATS_PERSISTENT> // OFF
2545  PT_create_stats_persistent_option;

2547 /**
2548  A template for options that set HA_CREATE_INFO::table_options and
2549  also records if the option was explicitly set.
2550 */
2551 template <ulong Property_flag, table_options_t Yes, table_options_t No>
2552 class PT_bool_create_table_option : public PT_create_table_option {
2553  typedef PT_create_table_option super;
2554 
2555  const bool value;
2556 
2557  public:
2558  explicit PT_bool_create_table_option(bool value) : value(value) {}
2559 
2560  bool contextualize(Table_ddl_parse_context *pc) override {
2561  if (super::contextualize(pc)) return true;
2562  pc->create_info->table_options &= ~(Yes | No);
2563  pc->create_info->table_options |= value ? Yes : No;
2564  pc->create_info->used_fields |= Property_flag;
2565  return false;
2566  }
2567 };

2790 class PT_create_table_stmt final : public PT_table_ddl_stmt_base {
2791  bool is_temporary;
2792  bool only_if_not_exists;
2793  Table_ident *table_name;
2794  const Mem_root_array<PT_table_element *> *opt_table_element_list;

2799  Table_ident *opt_like_clause;
2800 
2801  HA_CREATE_INFO m_create_info;
2802 
2803  public:
2804  /**
2805  @param mem_root MEM_ROOT to use for allocation
2806  @param is_temporary True if @SQL{CREATE @B{TEMPORARY} %TABLE}

2808  @param table_name @SQL{CREATE %TABLE ... @B{@<table name@>}}
2809  @param opt_table_element_list NULL or a list of table column and
2810  constraint definitions.
2811  @param opt_create_table_options NULL or a list of
2812  @ref ptn_create_or_alter_table_options
2813  "table options".
2814  @param opt_partitioning NULL or the @SQL{PARTITION BY} clause.
2815  @param on_duplicate DUPLICATE, IGNORE or fail with an error
2816  on data duplication errors (relevant
2817  for @SQL{CREATE TABLE ... SELECT}
2818  statements).
2819  @param opt_query_expression NULL or the @SQL{@B{SELECT}} clause.
2820  */
2821  PT_create_table_stmt(
2822  MEM_ROOT *mem_root, bool is_temporary, bool only_if_not_exists,
2823  Table_ident *table_name,
2824  const Mem_root_array<PT_table_element *> *opt_table_element_list,
2825  const Mem_root_array<PT_create_table_option *> *opt_create_table_options,
2826  PT_partition *opt_partitioning, On_duplicate on_duplicate,
2827  PT_query_primary *opt_query_expression)
2828  : PT_table_ddl_stmt_base(mem_root),
2829  is_temporary(is_temporary),
2830  only_if_not_exists(only_if_not_exists),
2831  table_name(table_name),
2832  opt_table_element_list(opt_table_element_list),
2833  opt_create_table_options(opt_create_table_options),
2834  opt_partitioning(opt_partitioning),
2835  on_duplicate(on_duplicate),
2836  opt_query_expression(opt_query_expression),
2837  opt_like_clause(nullptr) {}
2838  /**
2839  @param mem_root MEM_ROOT to use for allocation
2840  @param is_temporary True if @SQL{CREATE @B{TEMPORARY} %TABLE}.
2841  @param only_if_not_exists True if @SQL{CREATE %TABLE ... @B{IF NOT EXISTS}}.
2842  @param table_name @SQL{CREATE %TABLE ... @B{@<table name@>}}.
2843  @param opt_like_clause NULL or the @SQL{@B{LIKE @<table name@>}} clause.
2844  */
2845  PT_create_table_stmt(MEM_ROOT *mem_root, bool is_temporary,
2846  bool only_if_not_exists, Table_ident *table_name,
2847  Table_ident *opt_like_clause)
2848  : PT_table_ddl_stmt_base(mem_root),

2850  only_if_not_exists(only_if_not_exists),
2851  table_name(table_name),

2853  opt_create_table_options(nullptr),
2854  opt_partitioning(nullptr),
2855  on_duplicate(On_duplicate::ERROR),
2856  opt_query_expression(nullptr),
2857  opt_like_clause(opt_like_clause) {}
2858 
2859  Sql_cmd *make_cmd(THD *thd) override;

3738 class PT_alter_table_action : public PT_ddl_table_option {
3739  typedef PT_ddl_table_option super;
3740 
3741  protected:
3742  explicit PT_alter_table_action(Alter_info::Alter_info_flag flag)
3743  : flag(flag) {}
3744 
3745  public:
3746  bool contextualize(Table_ddl_parse_context *pc) override;
3747 
3748  protected:
3749  /**
3750  A routine used by the parser to decide whether we are specifying a full
3751  partitioning or if only partitions to add or to reorganize.
3752 
3753  @retval true ALTER TABLE ADD/REORGANIZE PARTITION.
3754  @retval false Something else.
3755  */
3756  bool is_add_or_reorganize_partition() const {
3757  return (flag == Alter_info::ALTER_ADD_PARTITION ||
3758  flag == Alter_info::ALTER_REORGANIZE_PARTITION);
3759  }
3760 
3761  public:
3762  const Alter_info::Alter_info_flag flag;
3763 };
